[[File:Greenland National Museum.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Greenland National Museum in Nuuk]]
The '''Greenland National Museum''' ({{lang-kl|Nunatta katersugaasivia allagaateqarfialu}}) is located in [[Nuuk]], the capital of [[Greenland]]. It was one of the first museums established in Greenland, inaugurated in the mid-1960s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.natmus.gl/Forsiden/tabid/80/language/en-US/Default.aspx |publisher=Greenland National Museum |title=The Museum |accessdate=12 August 2010}}</ref> The museum has many artefacts related to archaeology, history, art, and handicrafts and also has information about ruins, graveyards, buildings etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adopt.museum140.com/2012/07/17/46-national-museum-of-greenland/|title=#46 National Museum of Greenland  -  Adopt-a-Museum|website=adopt.museum140.com|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> It is based in a warehouse which was built in 1936.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/greenland/nuuk-town-godthab/sights/other/greenland-national-museum|title=Greenland National Museum|website=www.lonelyplanet.com|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>

==Qilakitsoq mummies==
A major display in the museum contains the [[Qilakitsoq|Qilakitsoq mummies]]. The mummies consist of three women and a six-month-old child, half of the mummies found at Qilakitsoq.

==Other displays==
The museum also houses a display on social change in the 1950s and one on geology. Several other nearby buildings also fall under the museums protection, such as the restocked cooper's workshop and a display on blubber vats and presses.

